    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1937-12-13T05:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1937-12-13T05:00:00-05:00" n="634"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d634">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">394.115 Panay/31: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Consul General at Shanghai</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gauss</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Shanghai</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1937-12-13T18:00:00+08:00"
                            >December 13, 1937—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received December 13—10:55 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1145. Confirming previous messages, Japanese Consul General informs me in writing
                    that following steps have been taken in connection with the <hi rend="italic"
                        >Panay</hi> incident:</p>
                <p>1. Japanese Military Attaché’s office asked the Military Headquarters to take
                    immediate measures in order to cease firing of the Japanese troops in and around
                    Hohsien in the vicinity of where the American citizens are.</p>
                <p>2. Instructions to cease firing were also conveyed by a naval plane to the
                    Japanese troops in and around Hohsien by dropping a communication ball
                    containing the message.</p>
                <p>3. Japanese gunboat <hi rend="italic">Hozu</hi> which is not very far from
                    Nanking was ordered immediately to proceed to the rescue of the American
                    citizens. Japanese naval authorities have also informed him that a naval flying
                    boat of a large type will be sent to Hohsien early tomorrow morning for rescue
                    purpose carrying a doctor, nurse and necessary medical supplies.</p>
                <p>Japanese authorities have been informed of the mission of British gunboat <hi
                        rend="italic">Bee</hi> and American gunboat <hi rend="italic">Oahu.</hi>
                </p>
                <p>Sent to Hankow, repeated to Department and Peiping.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Gauss</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
